As the spread of coronavirus has fed fears of illness, it has also spurred fears of mass quarantines.
Late on March 15, the National Security Council took to Twitter to knock down rumors about a national quarantine: "Text message rumors of a national #quarantine are FAKE.
Text message rumors of a national #quarantine are FAKE.
Here, we’ll attempt to clarify what’s accurate, and what’s not, about quarantines.
It’s been a century — back to the 1918-19 "Spanish flu" pandemic — since large-scale isolations and quarantines were last enforced.